1470
01:23:11.562 --> 01:23:11.562
Mm.

1471
01:23:11.562 --> 01:23:15.502
And so the reason I showed those examples from clinical trials in the beginning is

1472
01:23:15.532 --> 01:23:16.872
those are all core biopsies.

1473
01:23:16.892 --> 01:23:17.012
Yeah.

1474
01:23:17.022 --> 01:23:20.612
And we had to convince ourselves that sampling a little core biopsy, maybe two

1475
01:23:20.652 --> 01:23:23.972
passes through the needle, could still tell us about response.

1476
01:23:24.012 --> 01:23:26.772
And so I'm sort of convinced that even though we're not capturing the whole tissue,

1477
01:23:26.812 --> 01:23:30.672
we see that. But boy, it kind of alarms me when I look at the whole slide images

1478
01:23:31.052 --> 01:23:34.792
and you see the degree of heterogeneity there. It's pretty vast.

1479
01:23:34.892 --> 01:23:35.112
So we

1480
01:23:36.512 --> 01:23:39.832
have to be aware of what we're sampling and heterogeneity throughout, both at a

1481
01:23:39.872 --> 01:23:41.972
genomic and microenvironmental level.

1482
01:23:42.132 --> 01:23:43.312
Yeah. Absolutely. Thanks.

1483
01:23:43.332 --> 01:23:43.552
Thank you.

1484
01:23:46.892 --> 01:23:49.352
Fabulous talk and really excellent entire session.

