01:24:18.712 --> 01:24:22.512
rigorous enough to really predict at the individual level, but to

1494
01:24:23.172 --> 01:24:26.132
overlay that onto your data sets to

1495
01:24:27.272 --> 01:24:28.292
advance the field?

1496
01:24:28.972 --> 01:24:29.042
Yeah.

1497
01:24:29.052 --> 01:24:30.232
And not leave behind

1498
01:24:32.012 --> 01:24:34.592
grade of tumor. Can you see different grades?

1499
01:24:35.252 --> 01:24:38.132
Yeah. I wish I had a bit more time. I would've combined that.

1500
01:24:38.172 --> 01:24:41.492
So one of the things that we're using these very powerful digital pathology tools

1501
01:24:42.072 --> 01:24:44.472
is to basically have these

1502
01:24:45.672 --> 01:24:49.372
quantitative estimates of what we observe across the tissue, from the

1503
01:24:49.432 --> 01:24:52.532
tile level down to the individual pixel level.

1504
01:24:52.572 --> 01:24:55.552
And we're learning a lot of biology from these methods.

1505
01:24:55.642 --> 01:24:59.402
Now, some of the generative AI methods let us actually get towards, I

1506
01:24:59.412 --> 01:25:02.432
think the way we're viewing it is we can sort of get to its mechanistic

1507
01:25:02.452 --> 01:25:05.972
interpretability by asking, what's the transition, let's say, from a high risk to a

